SimpleNBAuthModule
public class SimpleNetFilterNBAuthModule
extends AbstractSimpleNBAuthModule

Network filter authentication module.

The purpose of this authentication module is to allow for filtering of inbound connections by address and transport protocol as a means of selecting an appropriate level of authentication for a given user (as opposed to an iptables approach which simnply prohibits or grants all access from certain network locations. A network filter may be used in conjunction with another authentication module to require additional or more appropriate authentication depending on the network location of the client connection (e.g., different passwords for local versus remote login, "priveleged" access for localhost users but not for remote users, etc.).

Note: This module does not perform any authentication protocol itself, but rather simply checks the connection data for the presence of the indicated attributes. Therefore, this module will only return authentication codes Accept or AuthenFail depending on whether the filter criteria are matched or not, respectively.

In the expectation that the same network access criteria would likely be applied to multiple users, this module uses the module definition portion of the SimpleNBAuthenticator Json configuration to define named network filters, which are then referenced in the user definition portion of the configuration. The JsonNode object used to define the network filter authentication module should include a "definitions" field name whose corresponding field value is a JsonNode object containing the named filter definitions. Each filter definition is a JsonNode object containing one or more of the following fields:

  • "addr" with a field value that is a string or an array of strings. Each string consists of a host (dotted IP or host name) optionally followed by a slash and high-order net-mask bit count (as per CIDR notation) if mask-bits are not specified or invalid (less than one or greater than address bits) then the specified host must match exactly. If a host name is specified, all addresses returned fron the DNS lookup are added to the list (with the specified net-mask). If more than one address entry is specified, the list matches if any entry matches the remote host of the client connection.
  • "addr_not" using the same syntax as "addr" but where the list matches if no entry matches the remote host of the client connection.
  • "port" with a field value that is an integer. This criteria returns true if the remote port of the client connection equals the specified value. This criteria is implemented by (and therefore identical to) setting both the port_low and the port_high values (if both are specified, the range criteria take precedence).
  • "port_low" with a field value that is an integer. This criteria returns true if the remote port of the client connection is greater than or equal to the specified value.
  • "port_high" with a field value that is an integer. This criteria returns true if the remote port of the client connection is less than or equal to the specified value.
  • "SSL" with a field value that is a string or an array of strings from the following list (returns true if the client connection type matches one of the strings):
    • "none" The socket is not an SSL socket.
    • "server" The socket is an SSL socket.
    • "client" The socket is an SSL socket with mutual authentication.
  • "and" with a field value that is a string or an array of strings that reference other previously defined filter names. This criteria returns false if any named filters return false and returns true otherwise (e.g., unspecified or an empty list).
  • "or" with a field value that is a string or an array of strings that reference other previously defined filter names. This criteria returns false if all named filters return false and returns true otherwise (e.g., unspecified or an empty list).
  • "and_not" with a field value that is a string or an array of strings that reference other previously defined filter names. This criteria returns false if all named filters return true and returns true otherwise (e.g., unspecified or an empty list).
  • "or_not" with a field value that is a string or an array of strings that reference other previously defined filter names. This criteria returns false if any named filters return true and returns true otherwise (e.g., unspecified or an empty list).
When more than one criteria are specified for a given filter definition, the result is the "and" of all of the criteria specified.

A SimpleNBAuthenticator user authentication rule element referencing this module requires the element definition node to consist of a string naming one filter rule to be applied. If the rule matches, Accept is returned. Otherwise, AuthenFail is returned.
